nodes.description: The CPRA is a ballot initiative that amends the CCPA, creating new consumer rights, establishing the CPPA, and strengthening enforcement.

Consumers' Right to Correct Inaccurate Personal Information
The Right to Know What Personal Information is Being Collected
The Right to Know What Personal Information is Sold or Shared and to Whom
The Right to Opt-Out of Sale or Sharing of Personal Information
The Right to Limit the Use and Disclosure of Sensitive Personal Information
The Right to Non-Discrimination for the Exercise of a Consumer's Privacy Rights
Mechanisms for Opting Out of Sale or Sharing
Private Right of Action for Data Breaches
Functions of the California Privacy Protection Agency

nodes.text: Inform consumers at or before the point of collection about the categories of personal information to be collected.
Do not collect additional categories of PI or use PI for incompatible purposes without providing notice.
Inform consumers of the length of time the business intends to retain each category of personal information.
Collection, use, retention, and sharing of PI shall be reasonably necessary and proportionate.
Implement reasonable security procedures and practices.
Ensure contracts with Service Providers, Contractors, and Third Parties are in place to protect PI.
Delete a consumer's personal information upon receipt of a verifiable consumer request.
Correct inaccurate personal information upon receipt of a verifiable consumer request.
Provide a clear and conspicuous link on the business’s Internet homepage(s), titled ’Do Not Sell or Share My Personal Information’.
Provide a clear and conspicuous link on the business’s Internet homepage(s), titled ’Limit the Use of My Sensitive Personal Information’.
Stop using and disclosing sensitive personal information for purposes other than those specified in the regulations upon request.
Do not discriminate against a consumer because the consumer exercised any of their rights.
Disclose information about consumer rights and how to exercise them in a privacy policy.
Ensure that the business’s privacy policy is updated at least once every 12 months.
Maintain reasonable security procedures to protect personal information from unauthorized access, theft, or disclosure.

nodes.name: Consumer
nodes.description: A natural person who is a California resident whose personal information is collected or processed by a business.

nodes.name: Business
nodes.description: An entity that collects personal information from California residents and determines the purposes and means of processing.

nodes.name: Service Provider
nodes.description: An entity that processes personal information on behalf of a business under a contract that restricts its use.

nodes.name: Contractor
nodes.description: A person to whom a business makes available a consumer's personal information for a business purpose.

nodes.name: Third Party
nodes.description: Any natural or legal person, public authority, agency or body other than the data subject, controller, processor and persons who under the direct authority of the controller or processor are authorized to process data.

nodes.name: California Privacy Protection Agency
nodes.description: State agency responsible for enforcing CPRA and establishing and publishing regulations.

nodes.name: California Attorney General
nodes.description: Responsible for enforcing CPRA and protecting consumer privacy rights.

nodes.name: Contents of Mail, Email, or Text Messages

Right to Non-Discrimination for Exercising CPRA Rights

nodes.description: Implement reasonable security procedures and practices appropriate to the nature of the personal information to protect from unauthorized or illegal access, destruction, use, modification, or disclosure.
Encrypt or redact personal information to render it unreadable in the event of a breach.
Contractual provisions prohibiting the retention, use, or disclosure of personal information for any purpose other than the specific business purpose defined in the contract.

Deidentify or aggregate consumer information so that it cannot reasonably identify, relate to, describe, be capable of being associated with, or be linked, directly or indirectly, to a particular consumer.

nodes.name: Point of Collection
nodes.description: The time at which a business collects personal information from a consumer.

nodes.name: Verifiable Consumer Request
nodes.description: A request made by a consumer to exercise their rights that the business can reasonably verify.

nodes.name: Global Privacy Control (GPC) Signal
nodes.description: An automated signal sent by a browser or device that communicates a consumer's choice to opt-out of the sale or sharing of their personal information.

nodes.name: Security Breach
nodes.description: Unauthorized access and exfiltration, theft, or disclosure of nonencrypted or nonredacted personal information.
Administrative fine for unintentional violations.
Administrative fine for intentional violations.
Administrative fine for violations involving the personal information of consumers under 16 years of age.

nodes.max_penalty: $750 per consumer, per incident, or actual damages
nodes.description: Private right of action for consumers in the event of a data breach resulting from failure to implement reasonable security.
